Polish Stocks Fall Most in 6 Months as PGNiG, PKO, KGHM Retreat

-- B y   K r y s t o f   C h a m o n i k o l a s
-- 
2011-02-17T17:29:57Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-17/polish-stocks-erase-gain-as-pgnig-and-telekomunikacja-decline.html
Poland’s benchmark stock index fell
the most in six months, led by commodity companies Polskie
Gornictwo Naftowe i Gazownictwo and  KGHM Polska Miedz SA , along
with PKO Bank Polski SA, the country’s biggest lender by assets.  The WIG20 gauge tumbled 1.7 percent to 2,641.83 at its 5:45
p.m. close in Warsaw, its biggest since Aug. 24.  Gornictwo, the country’s dominant gas company, also known
as PGNiG, lost 1.1 percent to 3.72 zloty, its lowest close in
two weeks. KGHM, the copper producer with the biggest European
output, fell 3.2 percent to 165.5 zloty, its lowest close since
Jan. 10. PKO slumped 2.2 percent, the most since Jan. 7, to 41
zloty.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Krystof Chamonikolas in Prague at 
